In [[linguistics]], a '''co-construction''' is a grammatical or semantic entity which has been uttered by more than one speaker.<ref>[http://www.sil.org/LINGUISTICS/glossary_fe/defs/AMDEn.pdf Lexique franco-anglais du modle d'analyse du discours modulaire genevois<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{ja icon}} [http://www.kokken.go.jp/public/eibun50_sup/JL7.html The National Institute for Japanese Language<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070221212710/http://www.kokken.go.jp/public/eibun50_sup/JL7.html |date=2007-02-21 }}</ref> It is a technical term for the notion of one person finishing another person's thought. For example:

:Person A: Excuse me, you could direct me to the, um...
:Person B: Bathroom?
:Person A: Yes, thank you.

