'''Juggling terminology''', [[juggling]] (especially [[toss juggling]]) terms:

{{glossary}}
{{term|Alternating/Asynchronous}}
{{defn|tosses or catches, where one hand makes a toss, then the second hand makes a toss, as opposed to ''synchronous''.}}
{{term|Asymmetrical}}
{{defn|juggling patterns with patterns whose length is an even number (and thus repeats on the same hand), as opposed to ''symmetrical''. For example, the [[shower (juggling)|shower pattern]].}}
{{term|Balance}}
{{defn|resting a prop on one's body or an object<ref>Darbyshire, Lydia; ed. (1993). ''Juggling'', p.79. Siddall, Jeremy; illustrations. Courage. {{ISBN|1-56138-224-8}}.</ref> for a beat or more}}
{{term|Beat}}
{{defn|the duration between consecutive tosses, tosses and catches, or catches. Beats are counted by siteswap.}}
{{term|Bounce}}
{{defn|allowing an object to bounce off a hard surface, typically the floor, before being caught.}}
{{term|[[Bounce juggling]]}}
{{defn|juggling including or consisting of bounces and catches.}}
{{term|Carry}}
{{defn|to move, or "carry", a ball with the first hand to the location it would have been caught at by the second hand instead of throwing it towards that spot, and to then throw it from that location using the first hand.}}
{{term|Catch}}
{{defn|when a ball lands on one's hand or is grabbed out of the air.}}
{{term|[[claw (juggling)|Claw]]/Snatch/Overhand}}
{{defn|where the hand throwing or catching a ball is turned upside down so that the palm of the hand faces the ground.}}
{{term|[[Contact juggling]]}}
{{defn|a form of object manipulation that focuses on the movement of objects such as balls in contact with the body (rolls or rolling).}}
{{term|Cross}}
{{defn|where one hand is passed over or under the other arm before throwing or catching.}}
{{term|Feed}}
{{defn|to pass a prop directly from one hand to the other. Siteswap: 1.}}
{{term|[[flash (juggling)|Flash]]}}
{{defn|to throw and catch each object, as many as possible, only once. A form of ''numbers juggling''. May also refer to patterns such as 55500 which allow a "flashy" move such as a clap or pirouette.}}
{{term|Half}}
{{defn|a variation of a pattern which may be more simple, sometimes may be used as preparation for, and generally resembles a truncated version of its namesake. For example the shower and the half-shower have siteswaps 51 and 3).}}
{{term|Hold time}}
{{defn|also "dwell time", the time, relative to the siteswap beats, which is a prop is held. Ladder diagrams often show no dwell time, with the prop landing at the same moment as its toss.}}
{{term|Inside}}
{{defn|to throw a prop in one hand under the prop just thrown or to be thrown. See: ''outside'' and ''reverse''.}}
{{term|[[multiplex (juggling)|Multiplex]]}}
{{defn|a toss of more than one object at a time. Also refers to ''patterns'' containing multiplexes. The reverse is a ''squeeze catch''.}}
{{term|[[juggling notation|Notation]]}}
{{defn|the written depiction of concepts and practices in juggling, such as [[siteswap]] and ''ladders''.}}
{{term|[[Numbers juggling]]}}
{{defn|juggling with as many objects as possible. See: ''flash'' and ''qualify''.}}
{{term|Orbit}}
{{defn|a ''carry'' where the held ball is move around another ball in a circle, as if orbiting. "Orbit" is also used in a technical sense to refer to, "the cycle of throws which a ball follows."<ref>Beever, Ben (2001). "[http://www.jugglingedge.com/pdf/BenBeeversGuidetoJugglingPatterns.pdf Siteswap Ben's Guide to Juggling Patterns]", p.37, ''JugglingEdge.com''. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150810153015/https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/15026487/GJP.pdf |date=August 10, 2015 |title=BenBeever.com }}, accessed: 11 3 2016.</ref> For example, the cascade (3) has one orbit while tennis (3) has two.}}
{{term|Outside}}
{{defn|to throw a prop in one hand over the prop just thrown or to be thrown. See: ''inside'' and ''reverse''.}}
{{term|Overhead}}
{{defn|"Juggling with your arms up in the air above your head & looking up from underneath the pattern,"<ref>"[https://www.twjc.co.uk/tut007.html Overhead cascade]", ''Tunbridge Wells Juggling Club''.</ref> such as the overhead cascade<ref>Darbyshire (1993), p.22.</ref>}}
{{term|Parity}}
{{defn|whether a pattern may be done only with an ''even'' or ''odd'' number of props or may be done either way. For example, the cascade may be done with any odd number of props greater than or equal to 3.}}
{{term|[[passing (juggling)|Pass]] }}
{{defn|to throw an object to another juggler.}}
{{term|[[juggling pattern|Pattern]]}}
{{defn|a specific manipulation of props during the practice of juggling.}}
{{term|Period}}
{{defn|the length of a pattern before it repeats. The cascade (3) has a period of 1 and the half-box (441) has a period of 3.}}
{{term|[[juggling prop|Prop]]}}
{{defn|an object used to juggle. If not a [[juggling ball|ball]], such as a [[bean bag]], objects used include [[juggling club]]s, [[juggling ring]]s,  [[cigar box (juggling)|cigar boxes]], [[knife juggling|knives]], and [[torch (juggling)|torches]].}}
{{term|Qualify or qualifying}}
{{defn|''numbers juggling'' where every prop must be thrown and caught at least twice, in contrast to a ''flash''.}}
{{term|Reverse}}
{{defn|tossing to the ''inside'' instead of the ''outside'', or the outside instead of the inside. For example, the [[cascade (juggling)|cascade]] and the [[reverse cascade]].}}
{{term|Shape distortion}}
{{defn|a variation of a pattern with the same siteswap but a different shape, such as the half-shower and the Statue of Liberty (both siteswap: 3, the latter uses overhead juggling).}}
{{term|Squeeze or squeeze catch}}
{{defn|the reverse of a ''multiplex'', where more than one ball is caught in the same hand simultaneously on the same beat.}}
{{term|Sticks/batons}}
{{defn|Wooden rods or [[doweling]], predates modern clubs.<ref>Darbyshire (1993), p.80.</ref>}}
{{term|Symmetrical}}
{{defn|juggling patterns with patterns whose length is an odd number (and thus repeats on the other hand), as opposed to ''asymmetrical''.}}
{{term|Synchronous}}
{{defn|tosses or catches made by each hand at the same time, as opposed to ''alternating''.}}
{{term|Toss}}
{{defn|a [[throwing|throw]] up into the air.}}
{{term|[[Toss juggling]]}}
{{defn|juggling consisting of tosses and catches.}}
{{term|[[Two-in-One (juggling)|Two-in-One]]}}
{{defn|[[Columns (juggling)#Variations|columns]], using one hand and two balls, "where the balls travel vertically in their own separate paths."<ref>"[http://www.libraryofjuggling.com/Tricks/3balltricks/Columns.html Columns]", ''LibraryofJuggling''. Accessed: October 20, 2016.</ref>}}
{{glossary end}}

