{{infobox language |name=Kaskian |nativename=Kaška |region=Northeastern [[Anatolia]] |ethnicity=[[Kaskians]] |era=Bronze Age |familycolor=unclassified |family=unclassified |iso3=zsk |linglist=zsk |glotto=none }}
'''Kaskian''' (Kaskean) was a non-[[Indo-European language]] of the [[Kaskians]] of northeastern [[Bronze Age]] Anatolia, in the mountains along the [[Black Sea]] coast.
It is sometimes suspected that Kaskian was related to the pre-Hittite [[Hattic language]], based on [[toponym]]s and personal names. There may also be connections to the [[Northwest Caucasian languages]]; the name ''Kaskian''<ref>Hittite ''Kaškaš'', Assyrian ''Kaška'', Egyptian ''Kškš''</ref> may be [[cognate]] with an old name for [[Circassia]],<ref>Arabic ''kašak'', Old Georgian ''kaški'', Old Armenian ''gašk'', Old Russian ''kasogi'', Ossetic ''kæsæg'', Byzantine Greek Κασαχία ''Kasakhía''</ref> and the name of one of the tribes in the Kaskian confederation, the Abešla, may be cognate with the endonym of the [[Abkhaz people]] and some Circassian people,<ref>Abkhaz Аҧсуа ''Apswa'', Old Georgian ''apsil-, apšil-'', Old Armenian ''apšeł-k'', Greek Αψίλαι ''apsílai'', Latin ''Absilae''</ref> suggesting the Kaskians proper and Abešla might have been the ancestors of the [[Circassians]] and other Caucasian peoples.<ref>George Hewitt, 1998. ''The Abkhazians'', p 49</ref> It has also been conjectured that Kaskian might belong to the [[Zan language|Zan]] family of languages, and have affinities to [[Megrelian]] or [[Laz language|Laz]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Singer |first=Itamar |date=2007 |title=Who were the Kaška? |url=https://colchianstudies.files.wordpress.com/2010/11/singer__kaska__phasis_20071.pdf|journal=Phasis |publisher=Ivane Javakhishvili Tblisi State University |volume=10 |issue=II |pages=178 |doi= |access-date=6 June 2018}}</ref>
